# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fautasi
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] The **Admiralty Islands** are an archipelago group of 40 islands in the Bismarck Archipelago, to the north of New Guinea in the South Pacific Ocean.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] These are also sometimes known as the **Manus Islands**, after the largest island of the chain.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] These rainforest-covered islands constitute Manus Province, the smallest and least-populous province of Papua New Guinea, in its Islands Region.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] The province had a population of 60,485 at the 2011 Census.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Many of the smaller Admiralty Islands are atolls and uninhabited.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] The larger islands in the center of the group are Manus Island and Los Negros Island.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] The other larger islands are Tong Island, Pak Island, Rambutyo Island and Lou Island to the east, Mbuke Island to the south and Bipi Island to the west of Manus Island.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Baluan Island, to the south of Manus Island, is the main island of the Pam Islands, where the Baluan-Pam language is spoken.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Other islands that have been noted as significant places in the history of Manus include Ndrova Island, Pityilu Island and Ponam Island.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] The temperature of the Admiralty Islands varies little throughout the year, reaching daily highs of 30–32 °C (86–90 °F) and 20–24 °C (68–75 °F) at night.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Average annual rainfall is 3,382 mm (133 in) and is somewhat seasonal, with June–August being the wettest months.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Manus reaches an elevation of 700 m (2,300 ft) and is volcanic in origin and probably broke through the ocean's surface in the late Miocene, 8–10 million years ago.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] The substrate of the island is either directly volcanic or from uplifted coral limestone.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] The main town in the islands is Lorengau on Manus, connected by road to an airport on nearby Los Negros Island, otherwise transport around the islands is by boat.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] There is little tourism, although the seas are attractive to divers, including Jean-Michel Cousteau who spent time on nearby Wuvulu Island in the 1970s.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Due to the isolated location, the rain forests of the Admiralty Islands are home to rare and endemic species of birds, bats and other animals, and are considered a separate ecoregion, the **Admiralty Islands lowland rain forests**.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] The majority of the forests on Manus still remain, but some of the smaller islands have been cleared for coconut farming.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] The typical tree species are various *Calophyllum* and *Sararanga* species.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] The 58.5 km2 (22.6 sq mi) Ndrolowa Wildlife Management Area was created in March 1985 south of Lorengau on Manus Island and contains both terrestrial and marine regions.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] A further 240 km2 (93 sq mi) protected area has been established around the highest mountain on Manus, Mount Dremsel, but the level of protection remains undetermined in the UNEP World Database on Protected Areas.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Three of the bird species endemic to Admiralty Islands have been listed as vulnerable in the IUCN Red List: Manus fantail (*Rhipidura semirubra*), superb pitta (*Pitta superba*) and Manus masked owl (*Tyto manusi*), and the Manus dwarf kingfisher (*Ceyx dispar*) listed as near threatened.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Three other birds are endemic to Admiralty Islands but are classified as non-threatened or least concern: white-naped friarbird (*Philemon albitorques*), Manus monarch (*Monarcha infelix*) and Manus hawk owl (*Ninox meeki*).
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] The islands are home to two endemic *Cornufer* frogs (*Cornufer admiraltiensis* and *Cornufer latro*) and four lizards, while the emerald green snail of Manus was the first terrestrial snail to be listed as vulnerable by the IUCN.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Along with New Guinea, the Bismarck Archipelago and the Solomon Islands Archipelago, the Admiralty Islands were first inhabited approximately 40,000 years ago, in the initial wave of migration out of Southeast Asia that also populated Australia.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] This early society appears to have cultivated taro, and to have deliberately introduced wild animals from New Guinea such as bandicoots and large rats.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Obsidian was gathered and traded throughout the Admiralty Islands archipelago.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] The Lapita culture arose around 3,500 years ago, and its extent ranged from the Admiralty Islands to Tonga and Samoa.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Its origins are contested, but it may well have been a product of another wave of migration from Southeast Asia.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Lapita society featured renowned pottery, stilt houses, the introduction of domestic animals such as pigs, dogs, and chickens, and substantial developments in agriculture and boat technology, allowing long-distance trade to develop.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Lapita society, as a distinct culture and extended trade network, collapsed around 2,000 years ago.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] The first European to visit the islands was the Spanish navigator Álvaro de Saavedra when trying to return from Tidore to New Spain in the summer of 1528.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Saavedra charted Manus as *Urays la Grande*.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Its visit was also reported in 1616 by the Dutch navigator Willem Schouten.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] The name 'Admiralty Islands' was devised by Captain Philip Carteret of the British Royal Navy in 1767.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Between 1884 and 1914 the area was administered as a German colony.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] In November 1914, the islands were occupied by troops of the Australian Naval and Military Expeditionary Force landed from the SS *Siar*.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] A few shots fired from a machine gun on *Siar* over the heads of the tiny German garrison at Lorengau were the last shots fired in the battle.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] After the war, the islands were governed by the Commonwealth of Australia under a League of Nations mandate.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Japanese troops landed on Manus Island on 7 April 1942.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] In 1944, Japanese forces occupying the islands were attacked and defeated by Allied forces in Operation Brewer.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Subsequently, a large American airbase and Manus Naval Base was built at Lombrum near Lorengau.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] Following Papuan independence in 1975, the Admiralty Islands became part of Papua New Guinea.
[src:fautasi/admiralty-islands] They became the Manus Province of the Islands Region in Papua New Guinea.
[src:fautasi/alingano-maisu] The concept for *Alingano Maisu* came about in 2001 when two Hawaiian voyaging groups, the Polynesian Voyaging Society and Na Kalai Waʻa Moku o Hawaiʻi, met with Piailug.
[src:fautasi/alingano-maisu] The two hulls of the 56-foot (17 m) vessel were fabricated by the Friends of *Hōkūleʻa* and *Hawaiʻiloa* on Oʻahu and shipped to the Island of Hawaiʻi where Na Kalai Waʻa completed construction of the canoe.
[src:fautasi/alingano-maisu] The Polynesian Voyaging Society provided much of the funding for the voyaging aspect of the project as well as an escort boat to help sail the canoe to Satawal.
[src:fautasi/alingano-maisu] The canoe is home-ported on the island of Yap under the command of Piailug's son, Sesario Sewralur.
[src:fautasi/alingano-maisu] Accompanied by *Hōkūleʻa*, the *Maisu* left Kawaihae, Hawaii, on January 18, 2007.
[src:fautasi/alingano-maisu] After stops in the Marshall Islands, Pohnpei, and Chuuk, the Maisu reached Satawal on March 15, 2007.
[src:fautasi/alingano-maisu] On March 18, while on Satawal, five native Hawaiian navigators on the voyage were inducted into pwo, a sacred Micronesian brotherhood of master navigators.
[src:fautasi/alingano-maisu] In June 2008, Palau Community College announced that there will be a one-year program in traditional non-instrumental navigation on the *Alingano Maisu* under Sesario Sewralur.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa consists of the eastern part of the Samoan archipelago – the inhabited volcanic islands of Tutuila, Aunuʻu, Ofu, Olosega and Taʻū and the uninhabited Rose Atoll – as well as Swains Island, a remote coral atoll in the Tokelau volcanic island group.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The total land area is 77 square miles (199 km2), slightly larger than Washington, D.C.; including its territorial waters, the total area is 117,500 square miles (304,000 km2), about the size of New Zealand.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa has a tropical climate, with 90 percent of its land covered by rainforests.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] As of 2024, the population is approximately 47,400 and concentrated on Tutuila, which hosts the capital and largest settlement, Pago Pago.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The vast majority of residents are indigenous ethnic Samoans, most of whom are fluent in the official languages, Samoan and English.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Inhabited by Polynesians since prehistoric times, American Samoa was first contacted by Europeans in the 18th century.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The islands attracted missionaries, explorers, and mariners, particularly to the highly protected natural harbor of Pago Pago.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The United States took possession of American Samoa in the late 19th century, developing it into a major naval outpost; the territory's strategic value was reinforced by the Second World War and subsequent Cold War.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In 1967, American Samoa became self-governing with the adoption of a constitution; its local government is republican in form, with separate executive, legislative, and judicial branches.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] It remains officially unorganized and is thus directly administered by the federal government.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Due to the territory's strategic location, the U.S. military has a significant presence and plays a major role in its economy and society.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The territory is noted for having the highest rate of military enlistment of any U.S. state or territory; as of 2021, the local U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Army recruiting station in Pago Pago ranked first in recruitment.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Tuna products are the main exports, with the U.S. proper serving as the largest trading partner.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Tourism is a nascent but underdeveloped sector, owing in part to the territory's relative geographic isolation, which also accounts for its high rate of poverty and emigration.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Since the Deeds of Cession were signed in 1900 and 1904, Samoans have avoided further integration into the U.S. system.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In 1949, the Department of the Interior moved to incorporate American Samoa through an Organic Act.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Afraid that incorporation might undermine the Samoan culture and traditional land ownership, Samoan matai intervened and Congress halted incorporation.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Instead, Samoa created its own government, the Samoan Fono, based on indigenous systems of governance.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Since then, Samoans have declined to establish a federal district court and refused birthright citizenship; Samoa remains the only U.S. territory with its own immigration system.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Many consider residents of American Samoa to be politically disenfranchised, with no voting representation in the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Congress, though American Samoa itself has a democratic system of governance.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] However, many Samoans have prioritized indigenous culture and government over integration into the United States.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is the only permanently inhabited territory of the United States in which citizenship is not granted at birth, and people born there are considered "non-citizen nationals" with limited rights.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] A primary reason that Samoans do not have birthright citizenship is that it is opposed by many Samoans, as evidenced by the unanimous resolution of the Samoan Fono in 2021 against birthright citizenship, and multiple statements and actions by government officials over the decades.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The elected representatives of American Samoan people unanimously fear that birthright citizenship would complicate the territory's political structure and lead to the erosion of indigenous governance, collective ownership of indigenous lands, and use of the Samoan language.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The origin of the name "Samoa" means "holy center", taken from a compound of the Samoan *sa* ("sacred") and *moa* ("center").
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The name is alternatively derived from a local chieftain named Samoa or an indigenous word meaning "place of the moa", a now-extinct bird, though the bird was known only from New Zealand.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Although the sovereign state of Samoa changed its name from Western Samoa in 1997, the territory is also sometimes referred to as *Eastern Samoa* to distinguish it from its neighbor.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Traditional oral literature of Samoa and Manuʻa talks of a widespread Polynesian network or confederacy (or "empire") that was prehistorically ruled by the successive Tui Manuʻa dynasties.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Manuan genealogies and religious oral literature also suggest that the Tui Manuʻa had long been one of the most prestigious and powerful paramounts of Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Oral history suggests that the Tui Manuʻa kings governed a confederacy of far-flung islands which included Tutuila, as well as smaller western Pacific chiefdoms and Polynesian outliers such as Uvea, Futuna, Tokelau, Tuvalu and bigger islands like the Samoa in the North.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Contact with Europeans began in the early 18th century.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Dutchman Jacob Roggeveen was the first known European to sight the Samoan Islands in 1722, calling them the "Baumann Islands" after one of his captains.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The next explorer to visit the islands was Louis-Antoine de Bougainville, who named them the "Îles des Navigateurs" in 1768.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] British explorer James Cook recorded the island names in 1773, but never visited.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The 1789 visit by Lapérouse was ended by an attack, on Tutuila island where Lapérouse's men were trying to obtain water.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] His second in command Capt. de Langle, and scientist Robert de Lamanon and several of his crew were surrounded by over a thousand Samoans and killed.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] La Pérouse named the island "Massacre Island", and the bay near Aasu is still called Massacre Bay.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] HMS *Pandora*, under the command of Admiral Edward Edwards (Royal Navy officer), visited the island in 1791 during its search for the H.M.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Mission work in the Samoas had begun in late 1830 when John Williams of the London Missionary Society arrived from the Cook Islands and Tahiti.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] By the late nineteenth century, French, British, German, and American vessels routinely stopped at Samoa, as they valued Pago Pago Harbor as a refueling station for coal-fired shipping and whaling.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The United States Exploring Expedition visited the islands in 1839.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Meade of the USS *Narragansett* sailed from Hawai'i to Pago Pago to explore the establishment of a U.S. naval station.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Peirce, the U.S. minister to Hawai'i, he was also tasked with negotiating a treaty that would secure American interests in Sāmoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The *Narragansett* reached Pago Pago on February 14, and Meade informed High Chief Mauga of his intention to lease land for a naval base.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Mauga granted the United States exclusive rights to build and maintain such a station in exchange for “the friendship and protection of the great government of the United States.” During his stay, Meade also arranged commercial port regulations for Pago Pago with Mauga.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In March 1889, an Imperial German naval force entered a village in Samoa, and in doing so destroyed some American property.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Three American warships then entered the Apia harbor and prepared to engage the three German warships found there.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Before any shots were fired, a typhoon wrecked both the American and German ships.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] A compulsory armistice was then called because of the lack of any warships.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Forerunners to the Tripartite Convention of 1899 were the Washington Conference of 1887, the Treaty of Berlin of 1889 and the Anglo-German Agreement on Samoa of 1899.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The following year, the U.S. formally annexed its portion, a smaller group of eastern islands, one of which contains the noted harbor of Pago Pago.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] After the United States Navy took possession of eastern Samoa for the United States government, the existing coaling station at Pago Pago Bay was expanded into a full naval station, known as United States Naval Station Tutuila and commanded by a commandant.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The Navy secured a Deed of Cession of Tutuila in 1900 and a Deed of Cession of Manuʻa in 1904 on behalf of the U.S. government.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The last sovereign of Manuʻa, the Tui Manuʻa Elisala, signed a Deed of Cession of Manuʻa following a series of U.S. naval trials, known as the "Trial of the Ipu", in Pago Pago, Taʻu, and aboard a Pacific Squadron gunboat.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Naval Station Tutuila, which was composed of Tutuila, Aunuʻu and Manuʻa, was officially renamed American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] People of Manuʻa had been unhappy since they were left out of the name "Naval Station Tutuila".
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In May 1911, Governor William Michael Crose authored a letter to the Secretary of the Navy conveying the sentiments of Manuʻa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The department responded that the people should choose a name for their new territory.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The traditional leaders chose "American Samoa", and, on July 7, 1911, the solicitor general of the Navy authorized the governor to proclaim it as the name for the new territory.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In 1918, during the final stages of World War I, the Great Influenza epidemic had taken its toll, spreading rapidly from country to country.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The result of Poyer's quick actions earned him the Navy Cross from the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] With this distinction, American Samoans regarded Poyer as their hero for what he had done to prevent the deadly disease.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The neighboring New Zealand territory at the time, Western Samoa, suffered the most of all Pacific islands, with 90% of the population infected; 30% of adult men, 22% of adult women and 10% of children died.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Poyer offered assistance to help his New Zealand counterparts but was refused by the administrator of Western Samoa, Robert Logan, who became outraged after witnessing the number of quarantine ships surrounding American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Angered by this, Logan cut off communications with his American counterparts.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] After World War I, during the time of the Mau movement in Western Samoa (then a League of Nations mandate governed by New Zealand), there was a corresponding American Samoa Mau movement led by Samuelu Ripley, a World War I veteran who was from Leone village, Tutuila.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] After meetings on the United States mainland, he was prevented from disembarking from the ship that brought him home to American Samoa and was not allowed to return because the American Samoa Mau movement was suppressed by the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Congress sent a committee to investigate the status of American Samoa, led by Americans who had a part in the overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Swains Island, which had been included in the list of guano islands appertaining to the United States and bonded under the Guano Islands Act, was annexed in 1925 by Pub.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] 68–75, following the dissolution of the Gilbert and Ellice Islands Protectorate by the United Kingdom.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Marines stationed in Samoa outnumbered the local population and had a huge cultural influence.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Young Samoan men from age 14 and above were combat-trained by U.S. military personnel.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Samoans served in various capacities during World War II, including as combatants, medical personnel, code personnel, and ship repairmen.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Department of Interior–sponsored attempt to incorporate American Samoa, was introduced in Congress.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] It was ultimately defeated, primarily through the efforts of Samoan chiefs, led by Tuiasosopo Mariota.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The efforts of these chiefs led to the creation of a territorial legislature, the American Samoa Fono, which meets in the village of Fagatogo.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In 1950 the Department of the Interior began to administer American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Navy-appointed governor was replaced by Peter Tali Coleman, who was locally elected.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Although technically considered "unorganized" since the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Congress has not passed an Organic Act for the territory, American Samoa is self-governing under a constitution that became effective on July 1, 1967.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Territory of American Samoa is on the United Nations list of non-self-governing territories, a listing which is disputed by the territorial government officials, who do consider themselves to be self-governing.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa and Pago Pago International Airport had historic significance with the Apollo Program.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The astronaut crews of Apollo 10, 12, 13, 14, and 17 were retrieved a few hundred miles from Pago Pago and transported by helicopter to the airport prior to being flown to Honolulu on C-141 Starlifter military aircraft.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] While the two Samoas share language and ethnicity, their cultures have recently followed different paths, with American Samoans often emigrating to Hawaiʻi and the U.S. mainland and adopting many U.S. customs, such as the playing of American football and baseball.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Samoans have tended to emigrate instead to New Zealand, whose influence has made the sports of rugby and cricket more popular in the western Samoan islands.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Travel writer Paul Theroux noted that there were marked differences between the societies in Samoa and American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] On August 13, 1999, the United Nations granted American Samoa "observer seat" status.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Six days later, American Samoa officially recognized both Samoan and English as its official languages.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In 2001 and 2003, the United States unsuccessfully sought to have American Samoa removed from the United Nations' decolonization list, arguing that the territory should not be considered a colony.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] American Samoans have a high rate of service in the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Because of economic hardship, military service has been seen as an opportunity in American Samoa and other U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The federal Fair Minimum Wage Act of 2007 started gradual adjustments to the territorial minimum wage to bring it up to the level for U.S. states.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] On December 13, 1784, French navigator Jean-François de Galaup, comte de Lapérouse landed two exploration parties on Tutuila's north shore: one from the ship *Boussole* at Fagasā, and the other from *L'Astrolabe* at Aʻasu.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] One of the cooks, David, died of "scorbutic dropsy".
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] This incident gave Samoa a reputation for savagery that kept Europeans away until the arrival of the first Christian missionaries four decades later.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] On December 12, at Aʻasu Bay, Lapérouse ordered his gunners to fire one cannonball amid the attackers who had killed his men the day before and were now returning to launch another attack.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] On December 19, 1912, English writer William Somerset Maugham arrived in Pago Pago, allegedly accompanied by a missionary and Miss Sadie Thompson.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] His visit inspired his short story "Rain" which later became plays and three major motion pictures.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The building still stands where Maugham stayed and has been renamed the Sadie Thompson Building.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Today, it is a prominent restaurant and inn.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] On November 2, 1921, American Samoa's 13th naval governor, Commander Warren Jay Terhune, died by suicide with a pistol in the bathroom of the government mansion, overlooking the entrance to Pago Pago Harbor.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] His body was discovered by Government House's cook, SDI First Class Felisiano Debid Ahchica, USN.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] His ghost is rumored to walk about the grounds at night.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] On August 17, 1924, Margaret Mead arrived in American Samoa aboard the SS *Sonoma* to begin fieldwork for her doctoral dissertation in anthropology at Columbia University, where she was a student of Professor Franz Boas.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Her work *Coming of Age in Samoa* was published in 1928, at the time becoming the most widely read book in the field of anthropology.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The book has sparked years of ongoing and intense debate and controversy.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Mead returned to American Samoa in 1971 for the dedication of the Jean P.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In 1938, the noted aviator Ed Musick and his crew died on the Pan American World Airways S-42 *Samoan Clipper* over Pago Pago, while on a survey flight to Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Sometime after takeoff, the aircraft experienced trouble, and Musick turned it back toward Pago Pago.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] While the crew dumped fuel in preparation for an emergency landing, an explosion occurred that tore the aircraft apart.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] On November 24, 1939, American Samoa's last execution to date was carried out.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] A man named Imoa of Fagatogo was convicted of stabbing a person named Sella to death and was hanged in the Customs House.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The popular Samoan song "Faʻafofoga Samoa" is based on this, said to be the final words of Imoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] On January 13, 1942, at 2:26 a.m., a Japanese submarine surfaced off Tutuila between Southworth Point and Fagasa Bay and fired about 15 shells from its 5.5-inch deck gun at the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Naval Station Tutuila over the next 10 minutes.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The first shell struck the rear of Frank Shimasaki's store, ironically owned by one of Tutuila's few Japanese residents.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Shimasaki had been interned as an enemy alien.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The next shell caused slight damage to the naval dispensary, the third landed on the lawn behind the naval quarters known as "Centipede Row," and the fourth struck the stone seawall outside the customs house.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The other rounds fell harmlessly into the harbor.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] As one writer described it, "The fire was not returned, notwithstanding the eagerness of the Samoan Marines to test their skill against the enemy ...
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] No American or Samoan Marines were wounded." Commander Edwin B.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Robinson was bicycling behind Centipede Row and was wounded in the knee by a piece of shrapnel, and "a member of the colorful native Fita Fita Guard" received minor injuries; they were the only casualties.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] On August 24, 1943, First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt visited American Samoa and inspected the Fita Fita Guard and Band and the First Samoan Battalion of U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The fact that First Lady reviewed the troops led to further assurance that Tutuila Island was considered safe.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Her presence underscored that World War II had passed by American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] While the Fita Fita band played, Eleanor Roosevelt inspected the guard.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] On October 18, 1966, President Lyndon Baines Johnson and First Lady Lady Bird Johnson visited American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Johnson dedicated the "Manulele Tausala" ("Lady Bird") Elementary School in Nuʻuuli, which was named after her.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Johnson is the only US president to have visited American Samoa, while Mrs.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Johnson was the second First Lady, preceded by Eleanor Roosevelt in 1943.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The territory's only hospital was renamed the LBJ Tropical Medical Center in honor of President Johnson.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In the late 1960s and early 1970s, American Samoa played a pivotal role in five of the Apollo Program missions.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The astronauts landed several hundred miles from Pago and were transported to the islands en route back to the mainland.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] President Richard Nixon gave three Moon rocks to the American Samoan government, which are currently on display in the Jean P.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Haydon Museum along with a flag carried to the Moon on one of the missions.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In November 1970, Pope Paul VI visited American Samoa in a brief but lavish greeting.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] On January 30, 1974, Pan Am Flight 806 from Auckland, New Zealand, crashed at Pago Pago International Airport at 10:41 pm, with 91 passengers aboard.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] 86 people were killed, including Captain Leroy A.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Four of the five surviving passengers were seriously injured, with the other only slightly injured.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The airliner was destroyed by the impact and succeeding fire.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The crash was attributed to poor visibility, pilot error, or wind shear since a violent storm was raging at the time.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In January 2014, filmmaker Paul Crompton visited the territory to interview local residents for a documentary film about the 1974 crash.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] As part of the Flag Day celebrations on April 17, 1980, a U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Navy P-3 Orion patrol plane from Patrol Squadron 50 took off with six skydivers from the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Army's Hawaii-based Tropic Lightning Parachute Club.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The airplane contacted the Solo Ridge-Mount Alava aerial tramway cable across Pago Pago harbor, which sheared off its vertical stabilizer.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The aircraft crashed, demolishing a wing of the Rainmaker Hotel and killing all six crew members and one civilian.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The six skydivers had already left the aircraft during a demonstration jump.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] On November 1, 1988, President Ronald Reagan signed a bill which created American Samoa National Park.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] On July 22, 2010, Detective Lieutenant Lusila Brown was fatally shot outside the temporary High Court building in Fagatogo.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] It was the first time in more than 15 years that a police officer was killed in the line of duty.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The last was Sa Fuimaono, who drowned after saving a teenager from rough seas.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] On November 8, 2010, United States Secretary of State and former First Lady Hillary Clinton made a refueling stopover at the Pago Pago International Airport.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] She was greeted by government dignitaries and presented with gifts and a traditional kava ceremony.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Mike Pence was the third sitting U.S. vice president to visit American Samoa (after Dan Quayle and Joe Biden) when he made a stopover in Pago Pago in April 2017.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] He addressed 200 soldiers here during his refueling stop.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Secretary of State Rex Tillerson visited town on June 3, 2017.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] On September 28, 2009, at 17:48:11 UTC, an 8.1 magnitude earthquake struck 120 miles (190 km) off the coast of American Samoa, followed by smaller aftershocks.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The quake occurred on the outer rise of the Kermadec-Tonga Subduction Zone.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] This is part of the Pacific Ring of Fire, where tectonic plates in the Earth's lithosphere meet, and earthquakes and volcanic activity are common.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The quake struck 11.2 miles (18.0 km) below the ocean floor and generated an onsetting tsunami that killed more than 170 people in the Samoa Islands and Tonga.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Four waves with heights from 15 feet (4.6 m) to 20 feet (6.1 m) high were reported to have reached up to one mile (1.6 km) inland on the island of Tutuila.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The Defense Logistics Agency worked with the Federal Emergency Management Agency to provide 16 ft × 16 ft (4.9 m × 4.9 m) humanitarian tents to the devastated areas of American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is classified in U.S. law as an unincorporated territory; the Ratification Act of 1929 vested all civil, judicial, and military powers in the President of the United States.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In 1951, with Executive Order 10264, President Harry Truman delegated that authority to the Secretary of the Interior.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] On June 21, 1963 Paramount Chief Tuli Leʻiato of Fagaʻitua was sworn in and installed as the first Secretary of Samoan Affairs by Governor H.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] On June 2, 1967, Interior Secretary Stewart Udall promulgated the Revised Constitution of American Samoa, which took effect on July 1, 1967.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The Governor of American Samoa is the head of government, and, along with the Lieutenant Governor of American Samoa, is elected on the same ticket by popular vote for a four-year term.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The governor's office is located in Utulei.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Since American Samoa is a U.S. territory, the President of the United States serves as the head of state but does not play a direct role in government.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The Secretary of the Interior oversees the government, retaining the power to approve constitutional amendments, overrides the governor's vetoes, and nomination of justices.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The legislative power is vested in the American Samoa Fono, which has two chambers.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The House of Representatives has 21 members serving two-year terms, being 20 representatives popularly elected from various districts and one delegate from Swains Island elected in a public meeting.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The Senate has 18 members, elected for four-year terms by and from the chiefs of the islands.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The judiciary of American Samoa is composed of the High Court of American Samoa, a District Court, and village courts.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The High Court and District Court are located in Fagatogo, near the Fono.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The High Court is led by a Chief Justice and an Associate Justice, appointed by the Secretary of the Interior.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Other judges are appointed by the governor upon the recommendation of the Chief Justice and confirmed by the Senate.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is an unincorporated and unorganized territory of the United States, administered by the Office of Insular Affairs, U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa's constitution was ratified in 1966 and came into effect in 1967.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] However, despite being de jure unorganized (as no Organic Act for it has been adopted by the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Congress, instead leaving power vested in the U.S. president), American Samoa is de facto organized, with its politics taking place in the framework of a presidential representative democratic dependency (whereby an elected Governor is head of government) and of a pluriform multi-party system.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Executive power is exercised by the governor.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Legislative power is vested in the two chambers of the legislature.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The American political parties (Republican and Democratic) exist in American Samoa, but few politicians are aligned with the parties.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The judiciary is independent of the executive and the legislature.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] There is also the traditional village politics of the Samoa Islands, the "faʻamatai" and the "faʻa Sāmoa", which continues in American Samoa and independent Samoa, and which interacts across these current boundaries.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The faʻa Sāmoa is the language and customs, and the faʻamatai are the protocols of the "fono" (council) and the chief system.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The faʻamatai and the fono take place at all levels of the Samoan body politic, from the family to the village, to the region, to national matters.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The ʻaiga is the family unit of Samoan society, which differs from the Western sense of a family in that it consists of an "extended family" based on the culture's communal socio-political organization.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The matai (chiefs) are elected by consensus within the fono of the extended family and village(s) concerned.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The matai and the fono, which are themselves made of matai, decide on the distribution of family exchanges and tenancy of communal lands.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The majority of lands in American Samoa and independent Samoa are communal.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] A matai can represent a small family group or a great extended family that reaches across islands and to both American Samoa and independent Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In 2010, voters rejected a package of amendments to the territorial constitution, which would have, among other things, allowed U.S. citizens to be legislators only if they had Samoan ancestry.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In 2012, both the Governor and American Samoa's delegate to the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Congress Eni Faleomavaega called for the populace to consider a move toward autonomy if not independence, with a mixed response.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] According to the Immigration and Nationality Act (INA), the people born in American Samoa – including those born on Swains Island – are "nationals but not citizens of the United States at birth".
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] If a child is born on any of these islands to any U.S. citizen, then that child is considered a national and a citizen of the United States at birth.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] All U.S. nationals have statutory rights to reside in all parts of the United States, and may apply for citizenship by naturalization after three months of residency by paying a fee, passing a test in English and civics, and taking an oath of allegiance to the United States.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] All U.S. nationals also have the right to work in the United States, except in certain government jobs that specifically require U.S. citizenship.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The question of whether American Samoans should be granted citizenship is controversial in American Samoa, and the government of American Samoa is currently opposed to it.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Those against citizenship worry that it would lead to federal judges overturning American Samoa's unique political system and land ownership customs, in which one must be at least 50% of Samoan ancestry to acquire land and land ownership is controlled by local families and *matai*.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Those in favor of citizenship claim the law discriminates against them unfairly, restricting their voting rights and their ability to serve in many public sector professions.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In 2012, a group of American Samoans sued the federal government seeking recognition of birthright citizenship for American Samoans in the case *Tuaua v.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In an *amicus curiae* brief filed in federal court, American Samoan Congressman Faleomavaega supported the legal interpretation that the Citizenship Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment does not extend birthright citizenship to United States nationals born in unincorporated territories.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia affirmed that Fourteenth Amendment citizenship guarantees did not apply to persons born in unincorporated territories and a year later the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Supreme Court declined to review the lower court's decision.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] On July 20, 2021, the Legislature of American Samoa unanimously passed a resolution in support of the 10th Circuit Court's decision to reverse.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] As U.S. nationals, American Samoans can vote in local elections in the territory; however, if they live in other parts of the United States, they are not allowed to vote in federal, state or the vast majority of local elections unless they become U.S. citizens.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The only federal office American Samoans elect directly is a non-voting delegate to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Since the delegate's office was created in 1978, three people have held the seat: Democrat Fofō Iosefa Fiti Sunia (1981–1988); Democrat Eni Faleomavaega (1989–2015); and Republican Aumua Amata Radewagen (2015–).
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] American Samoans also participate in partisan presidential primaries, as well as send delegates to the Democratic and Republican National Conventions.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Unique among U.S. territories, American Samoa has its own immigration law, separate from the laws that apply in other parts of the United States.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] U.S. nationals may freely reside in American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The American Samoan government, via its Immigration Office, controls the migration of foreign nationals to the islands.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Special application forms exist for migration to American Samoa based on family or employment sponsorship.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Unlike all other permanently inhabited U.S. jurisdictions (states, District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Virgin Islands, Guam and Northern Mariana Islands), American Samoa is not considered a U.S. state for the purposes of the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] As a result, there is no path for immigrants to American Samoa to apply for U.S. citizenship, or U.S. nationality at all, without permanent residence in another U.S. jurisdiction.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In addition, foreign nationals who do have lawful permanent residence in the United States may be considered to have abandoned it if they have moved to live in American Samoa, and time spent there does not count in the required period of U.S. presence for naturalization.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] U.S. nationals without U.S. citizenship (the status of most American Samoans) have the right to reside in all parts of the United States without immigration restrictions.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] They also have the same rights as lawful permanent residents to sponsor foreign family members to immigrate to the United States (they may sponsor spouses and unmarried children), but not the same rights as U.S. citizens (who may also sponsor parents, married children, and siblings).
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Under American Samoan law, land ownership is subject to racial restrictions.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Since 1900, there have been three main categories of land ownership: native, individual, and freehold.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Native land, which makes up over 90% of all land in the territory, is land under the communal ownership of an ʻaiga, as opposed to the private ownership of an individual.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Freehold land, which makes up only about 2% of the total, is land which was granted to foreigners before the U.S. took possession of the territory in 1900 and whose owners have not chosen to revert to native or individual land status.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The American Samoa Code (Annotated) prohibits the transfer of ownership (whether by sale or otherwise) of any land other than freehold land to any person who has less than one-half native Samoan blood, which in this context includes both American and Western Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In addition, it is prohibited to transfer ownership of any native (communal) land to any person who is not a full-blooded native Samoan: this includes any person who has any non-native blood whatsoever, even if they are more than one-half native Samoan.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] 10, 14 (1980), the Appellate Division of the High Court of American Samoa held that while these laws created a classification based on race, they did not violate the guarantees of equal protection and due process contained in the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Constitution and the Revised American Samoan Constitution.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Embassy in Samoa notes that: "In July 1997 the Constitution was amended to change the country's name from Western Samoa to Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Samoa had been known simply as Samoa in the United Nations since joining the organization in 1976.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The neighboring U.S. territory of American Samoa protested the move, feeling that the change diminished its own Samoan identity.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is administratively divided into three districts – Western, Eastern and Manuʻa – and two "unorganized" atolls, Swains Island and the uninhabited Rose Atoll.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The districts are subdivided into counties and villages.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Pago Pago, often cited as the capital of American Samoa, is one of the largest villages and is located on the central part of Tutuila island in Maʻoputasi County.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa, located within the geographical region of Oceania, is one of only two possessions of the United States in the Southern Hemisphere, the other being Jarvis Island.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Its total land area is 76.1 square miles (197.1 km2) – slightly larger than Washington, D.C. – consisting of five rugged, volcanic islands and two coral atolls.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The five volcanic islands are Tutuila, Aunuʻu, Ofu, Olosega, and Taʻū.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The coral atolls are Swains and Rose Atoll.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Of the seven islands, Rose Atoll is the only uninhabited one; it is a Marine National Monument.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is the southernmost reach of the United States at fourteen degrees below the equator.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Due to its positioning in the South Pacific Ocean, it is frequently hit by tropical cyclones between November and April.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Rose Atoll is the easternmost point of the territory.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa's Rose Atoll is the southernmost point of the United States.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is home to the National Park of American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Mount Pioa, nicknamed the Rainmaker, is 1,718 ft (524 m).
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is also home to some of the world's highest sea cliffs at 3,000 ft (910 m).
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The Vailuluʻu seamount, an active submerged volcano, lies 28 miles (45 km) east of Taʻū in American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] It was discovered in 1975 and has since been studied by an international team of scientists, contributing towards understanding of the Earth's fundamental processes.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Growing inside the summit crater of Vailuluʻu is an active underwater volcanic cone, named after Samoa's goddess of war, Nafanua.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In American Samoa forest cover is around 86% of the total land area, equivalent to 17,130 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, down from 18,070 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] In 2020, naturally regenerating forest covered 17,130 hectares (ha) and planted forest covered 0 hectares (ha).
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest 1% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and around 15% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] For the year 2015, 0% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership, 100% private ownership and 0% with ownership listed as other or unknown.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa lies within two terrestrial ecoregions: Samoan tropical moist forests and Western Polynesian tropical moist forests.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa has a tropical climate all year round with two distinct seasons, the wet and dry season.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The wet season is usually between December and March and the dry season is from April through to September with the average daily temperature around 81–83 °F (27–28 °C) all year round.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The climate is warm, tropical, and humid, averaging around 80 °F or 26.7 °C, with a variation of about 15 °F or 8 °C during the year.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The southern hemisphere winter, from June to September, is the coolest time of the year.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The summer months of December to March bring hotter temperatures, while the months from April to November are considered the "dry" season.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Throughout the year, however, rain follows clouds blown in by the trade winds that rise from the east almost daily.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The mountains of the Pago Pago area, standing over Pago Pago Harbor, catch these clouds, bringing an average of 200 inches or 5,100 millimeters of rainfall per year.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Climate change in American Samoa encompasses the effects of climate change, attributed to man-made increases in atmospheric carbon dioxide, in the U.S. territory of American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The American Samoa Environmental Protection Agency (ASEPA) notes that the territory "has a fragile ecosystem" which is "directly and immediately impacted by global climate change".
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] The Human Rights Measurement Initiative finds that the climate crisis has worsened human rights conditions in American Samoa slightly (2.3 out of 6).
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p01] Human rights experts provided that the climate crisis has affected shores, fishers and resource availability, and that only a small group of people are able to connect the climate crisis with existing human rights conditions.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The economic health of American Samoa reflects the trends in other populated U.S. territories, which are in turn dependent on federal appropriations.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Federal dollars enter the economy through congressional appropriations, categorical grants, Social Security payments, and payments to Samoans retired from the military.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Tuna canning is the backbone of the American Samoa economy.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Cannery employment and local auxiliary businesses provide additional revenues for the territorial government.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In the mid-1960s, efforts began to develop a tourism industry in American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Efforts were delayed due to issues with inconsistent airline service, insufficient high-quality accommodations, and the lack of well-trained workers in the hospitality and tourism industries.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Agriculture and fishing still provide sustenance for local families.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Employment on the island falls into three relatively equal-sized categories of approximately 5,000 workers each: the public sector, the single remaining tuna cannery, and the rest of the private sector.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] There are only a few federal employees in American Samoa and a few active duty military personnel, except members of the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Coast Guard, military recruiters, and some Full-Time Support staff at the Pele Army Reserve unit that maintains the facility and provides cadre, training, and logistics support.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The Pele US Army Reserve Center is in Tafuna, and a U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Army and United States Marine Corps recruiting station is in Nuʻuuli.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The overwhelming majority of public sector employees work for the American Samoa territorial government.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] One tuna cannery is StarKist, which exports several hundred million dollars' worth of canned tuna to the United States each year.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In early 2007, the Samoan economy was highlighted in the Congress at the request of Eni Faleomavaega, the Samoan delegate to the United States House of Representatives, as it was not mentioned in the minimum wage bill.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] It was given no exemption from the coming increases, which he protested as unfair to the Samoan economy.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] House Speaker Nancy Pelosi initially granted his request for an exemption, but backed down after being accused of serving special interests, since tuna packing company Chicken of the Sea was based in her district.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Samoa Packing, a Chicken of the Sea subsidiary closed in 2009, citing both minimum wage increases and increasing foreign competition, with the latter as the "main reason".
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Minimum wage in Samoa has been the topic of much debate, with the Samoan government and Chamber of Commerce strongly opposed, while businesses and workers hold nuanced views.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] From 2002 to 2007, real GDP of American Samoa increased at an average annual rate of 0.4 percent.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The annual growth rates of real GDP ranged from −2.9 percent to +2.1 percent.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The volatility in the growth rates of real GDP was primarily accounted for by changes in the exports of canned tuna.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The tuna canning industry was the largest private employer in American Samoa during this period.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In 2017, GDP in American Samoa decreased by 5.8%, but in 2018 it increased by 2.2%.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] From 2002 to 2007, the population of American Samoa increased at an average annual rate of 2.3 percent, and real GDP per capita decreased at an average annual rate of 1.9 percent.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Agricultural production covers for domestic needs and only a small share of fruits and vegetables are exported.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] According to figures as of 2013, the ratio between import and export is almost balanced.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Many residents rely on transfer payments from relatives living on the mainland or from federal subsidies.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The unemployment rate was 29.8% in 2005 but improved to 23.8% as of 2010.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In 2020, American Samoa's GDP was $709 million.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The Fair Labor Standards Act of 1938 has contained special provisions for American Samoa since its inception, citing its limited economy.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] American Samoan wages are based on the recommendations of a Special Industry Committee meeting bi-annually.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Originally, the act contained provisions for other territories, provisions which were phased out as those territories developed more diverse economies.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In 2007, the Fair Minimum Wage Act of 2007 was passed, increasing the minimum wage in American Samoa by 50¢ per hour in 2007 and another 50¢ per hour each year thereafter until the minimum wage in American Samoa equals the federal minimum wage of $7.25 per hour in the United States.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In response to the minimum wage increase, the Chicken of the Sea tuna canning plant was shut down in 2009, and 2,041 employees were laid off in the process.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The other major tuna canning plant in American Samoa is StarKist, which began laying off workers in August 2010, with plans to lay off a total of 800 workers due to the minimum wage increases and other rising operation costs.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa Governor Togiola Tulafono suggested that, rather than laying off minimum wage workers, the companies could reduce salaries and bonuses of top-tier employees.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] As in other U.S. territories, the U.S. federal government imposes payroll taxes and the equivalent self-employment tax on income from work in American Samoa, but not the federal income tax on income generated in American Samoa by its residents (except from work as U.S. government employees).
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Instead, the government of American Samoa itself taxes the worldwide income of its residents, as well as the income generated there by nonresidents, largely under the same rules and rates as the U.S. tax code in effect in 2000, with certain modifications such as a minimum tax rate of 4%.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] A similar situation applies to corporations.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In 1983, the use of citizenship in taxation by American Samoa (due to its incorporation of the U.S. tax code) was ruled unconstitutional.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] However, these taxes still apply to residents of a U.S. territory who acquired U.S. citizenship by birth or naturalization in a different part of the U.S. or by descent.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] It has been argued that this distinction based on place of birth, and not only residence or citizenship, is a rare case of unconstitutional tax discrimination, but it has never been challenged in court.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The government of American Samoa itself does not impose estate or gift taxes.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] U.S. citizens (or anyone) cannot acquire this status after birth.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa does not impose a sales tax, but it imposes a general import tax of 8%.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa is an independent customs territory, whose importation rules and taxes differ from those applicable to other parts of the United States.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Some aspects of telecommunications in American Samoa are, like other U.S. territories, inferior to that of the mainland United States; a recent estimate showed that American Samoa's Internet speed is slower than that of several Eastern European countries.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In 2012 Michael Calabrese, Daniel Calarco, and Colin Richardson stated that American Samoa had the most expensive internet of any U.S. territory and that the speeds were only slightly superior to those of dial-up internet in the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] They also stated that many American Samoans are too poor to afford "high-speed internet".
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa has 150 miles (240 km) of highways (estimated in 2008).
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The maximum speed limit is 30 miles per hour.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Ports and harbors include Aunuʻu, Auasi, Faleasao, Ofu and Pago Pago.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The territory has three airports, all of which have paved runways.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The main airport is Pago Pago International Airport, on the island of Tutuila.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The Manuʻa group has two airports: Ofu Airport on the island of Ofu, and Fitiuta Airport on the island of Taʻū.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] According to a 1999 estimate, the territory has no merchant marine.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] On June 8, 1922, the first bus service on Tutuila began its operations.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The *ʻaiga* bus system travels across the island of Tutuila.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] As of 2022, the population of American Samoa is estimated around 45,443 people.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The 2020 census counted 49,710 people, 97.5% of whom lived on the largest island, Tutuila.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] About 57.6% of the population were born in American Samoa, 28.6% in independent Samoa, 6.1% in other parts of the United States, 4.5% in Asia, 2.9% in other parts of Oceania, and 0.2% elsewhere.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] At least 69% of the population had a parent born outside American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa is small enough to have just one ZIP code, 96799, and uses the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Postal Service (state code "AS") for mail delivery.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In the 2020 census, 89.4% of the population reported at least partial Samoan ethnicity, 83.2% only Samoan, 5.8% Asian, 5.5% other Pacific island ethnicities, 4.4% mixed, and 1.1% other ethnicities.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The Samoan language was spoken at home by 87.9% of the population, while 6.1% spoke other Pacific island languages, 3.3% spoke English, 2.1% spoke an Asian language, and 0.5% spoke other languages; 47.2% of the population spoke English at home or "very well".
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In 2022, Samoan and English were designated as official languages of the territory.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] At least some of the deaf population use Samoan Sign Language.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Major Christian denominations on the island include the Congregational Christian Church in American Samoa, the Catholic Church, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, and the Methodist Church of Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Collectively, these churches account for the vast majority of the population.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Gordon Melton in his book claims that Methodists, Congregationalists with the London Missionary Society, and Catholics led the first Christian missions to the islands.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Other denominations arrived later, beginning in 1895 with the Seventh-day Adventists, various Pentecostals (including the Assemblies of God), Church of the Nazarene, Jehovah's Witnesses and The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] CIA Factbook 2010 estimate shows the religious affiliations of American Samoa as 98.3% Christian, other 1%, unaffiliated 0.7%.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] World Christian Database 2010 estimate shows the religious affiliations of American Samoa as 98.3% Christian, 0.7% agnostic, 0.4% Chinese Universalist, 0.3% Buddhist and 0.3% followers of the Baháʼí Faith.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] According to Pew Research Center, 98.3% of the total population is Christian.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Among Christians, 59.5% are Protestant, 19.7% are Catholic and 19.2% are other Christians.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] A major Protestant church on the island, gathering a substantial part of the local Protestant population, is the Congregational Christian Church in American Samoa, a Reformed denomination in the Congregationalist tradition.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] As of April 2023, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints website claims a membership of 16,512 (nearly 30% of American Samoa's entire population), with 43 congregations and five family history centers.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Jehovah's Witnesses claim 210 "ministers of the word" and three congregations.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The Catholic Church has at least 18 churches in the territory and 29 parishes under the Diocese of Samoa-Pago Pago (Diœcesis Samoa-Pagopagensis) which was created in 1982 by Pope John Paul II through the bull *Studiose quidem* and constitutes a suffragan see of the Archdiocese of Samoa-Apia.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The bishop has his see in the Cathedral of the Holy Family in Tafuna and in the Co-cathedral of St.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Of the ten secondary schools, five are operated by the American Samoa Department of Education; the other five are either administered by religious denominations or are privately owned.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa Community College, founded in 1970, provides post-secondary education on the islands.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa was home to one high school as of 1961, which existed due to the matai's pressure on the naval governor to transform the old Marine barracks at Utulei into a school.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The teenagers of well-off and more politically connected families attended the school, which would later be known as Samoana High School.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] With a median age of 15, the demand for more high schools was increasing, and three new high schools were established by 1968.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Another two soon followed, and by 1979, 2,800 high school students were attending six public and private high schools in American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Looking for a cost-effective way for educational reformation, Governor H.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Rex Lee introduced the public television system in 1964.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] When TV was introduced, there were 6,000 educational programs produced annually; by 1981, only one series comprising 40-minute lessons in English-language skills was still aired.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] One of the side effects of advertising in popular programming from the U.S. was an increase in sales of over-the-counter drugs such as Pepto-Bismol and Sominex, with television being directly blamed for the decline of village life.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The Samoan culture has developed over 3,500 years and largely withstood interaction with European cultures.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] It was adapted well to the teachings of Christianity.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The Samoan language is still in use in daily exchange; however, English is widely used and also the legal official language.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Besides Samoan language classes and cultural courses, all instructions in public schools are in English.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The basic unit of the American Samoa culture is the *ʻaiga* (family).
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] It consists of both immediate and extended family.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The *matai*, or chief, is the head of the ʻaiga.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The chief is the custodian of all ʻaiga properties.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] A village (nuʻu) is made up of several or many ʻaiga with a common or shared interest.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Each ʻaiga is represented by their chief in the village councils.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The music of Samoa is a complex mix of cultures and traditions, with pre- and post-European contact histories.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Since American colonization, popular traditions such as rap and hip hop have been integrated into Samoan music.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Traditional Samoan musical instruments includes several different distinctive instruments, including a fala, which is a rolled-up mat beaten with sticks and several types of slit drum.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The main sports played in American Samoa are football, Samoan cricket, canoeing, yachting, basketball, golf, netball, tennis, rugby, table tennis, boxing, bowling, volleyball, and fishing tournaments.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Some current and former sports clubs are the American Samoa Tennis Association, Rugby Unions, Lavalava Golf Club, and Gamefish Association.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Leagues improved and organized better after the completion of the Veterans Memorial Stadium.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The 1997 South Pacific Mini Games were the biggest international event ever to take place in American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The bid to host the games for the 23 participating countries was approved in May 1993.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Lutali appointed Fuga Teleso to head the task force charged with game preparations, including the construction of a stadium.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The Governor later handed the task force on preparations to Lieutenant Governor Togiola.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The task force merged with the American Samoa National Olympics Committee to better coordinate and facilitate preparations.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Willis Construction built the 1,500-seat stands.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The Department of Public Safety trained its force for special games security.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The opening ceremony became extravagant where the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Army Reserve carried the torch from Tula and Leone.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] About 2,000 athletes, coaches, and sponsors attended from 19 countries and competed in 11 sports at the game.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa fielded a team of 248 athletes.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The team won 48 medals, 22 of which were gold medals, and American Samoa came in fourth overall in the ratings.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa Rotary Club honored Fuga Tolani Teleso with the community's top award, the Paul Harris Fellowship Award, for his work on constructing the Veterans Memorial Stadium.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In 1982, yachters competed in the Hobie World Championship held in Tahiti.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa beat the Apia team by half a point and won the Samoa Cup.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In 1983, a team coached by Adele Satele-Galeai brought home the winning trophy from the Regional women's volleyball tournament in Hawaii.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Also in 1983, the South Pacific Games were held in Apia.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa received 13 medals: four gold, four silver, and five bronze.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] That same year, three junior golfers made the cut out of 1,000 players to attend the World Junior Golf Tournament in San Diego, California.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In 1987, American Samoa became the 167th member of the International Olympic Committee.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The first South Pacific Junior Tennis Tournament was held at the Tafuna courts in January 1990.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Tony Solaita was the first American Samoan to play in Major League Baseball.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] There are thirty players from American Samoa in the National Football League (NFL) as of 2015 and over 200 play Div.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Some American Samoan NFL football players are Shalom Luani, Junior Siavii, Jonathan Fanene, Mosi Tatupu, Shaun Nua, Isaac Sopoaga, and Daniel Teʻo-Nesheim.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] After World War II, a Welfare and Recreation Department was created.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] This department arranged bowling, softball, badminton tournaments, basketball, and volleyball at various Tutuila locations.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Boxing matches and dancing also became popular activities.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] About 30 ethnic Samoans, all from American Samoa, currently play in the National Football League, and more than 200 play NCAA Division I college football.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In recent years, it has been estimated that a Samoan male (either an American Samoan, or a Samoan living in the mainland United States) is anywhere from 40 to 56 times more likely to play in the NFL than a non-Samoan American, giving American Samoa the nickname "Football Islands".
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Samoans are the most disproportionately overrepresented ethnic group in the National Football League.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Six-time All-Pro Junior Seau was one of the most famous Americans of Samoan heritage ever to play in the NFL, having been elected to the NFL 1990s All-Decade Team and Pro Football Hall of Fame.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The football culture was featured on *60 Minutes* on January 17, 2010.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] At the 2016 Republican National Convention, American Samoa's delegation said American Samoa is "the greatest exporter of NFL players".
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The Football Federation American Samoa oversees men's and women's national teams.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The men's national team made its international debut in the 1983 South Pacific Games, losing its opener against Western Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Despite scoring a win against Wallis and Futuna, the team did not exit the group stage.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The team lost to Australia 31–0 in a FIFA World Cup qualifying match on April 11, 2001, but on November 22, 2011, they finally won their first FIFA World Cup qualifier, beating Tonga 2–1.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The appearance of American Samoa's Jaiyah Saelua, who is faʻafafine, in the contest "apparently became the first transgender player to compete on a World Cup stage".
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The women's national team made its international debut at the 1998 OFC Women's Championship, losing both of its matches: 21–0 to Australia and 9–0 to Papua New Guinea.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The American Samoan men's national team features in the highly rated 2014 British film *Next Goal Wins*.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The film documents the team's 2014 FIFA World Cup qualifying campaign, in which they achieved their first-ever international win.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Saelua and Nicky Salapu, the man famous for being the goalkeeper during the team's 31–0 loss to Australia in 2001, feature prominently in the film.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] A feature film adaptation of the documentary was released in 2023 and was directed by Taika Waititi.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The American Samoa national rugby league team represents the country in international rugby league.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The team competed in the 1988, 1992, 1998 and 2004 Pacific Cup competitions.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The team has also competed in the 2003 and 2004 World Sevens qualifiers in the 2005 World Sevens.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] America Samoa's first match in the international Rugby League was in the 1988 Pacific Cup against Tonga, Tonga won the match 38–14 which is still the biggest loss by an American Samoan side.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa's biggest win was in 2004 against New Caledonia with a final score of 62–6.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa gets broadcasts of the National Rugby League in Australia on free-to-air television.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] There is also a new movement that aims to set up a four-team domestic competition in American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Rugby union is a growing sport in American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The first rugby game recorded in American Samoa was in 1924, since then the development of the game had been heavily overshadowed by the influence of American football during the 1970s.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The highest governing body of rugby in American Samoa is the American Samoa Rugby Union which was founded in 1990 and was not affiliated with the IRB until 2012.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Internationally, two American Samoans have played for the New Zealand national rugby union team, known as the All Blacks.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Frank Solomon (born in Pago Pago) became the first American national of Samoan descent to play for a New Zealand team.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Considered a pacific pioneer in New Zealand rugby, Solomon scored a try against Australia in the inaugural Bledisloe Cup match in 1932, which New Zealand won 21–13.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The second American Samoan to play for the All Blacks is Jerome Kaino (born in Fagaʻalu).
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] A native of Leone, Kaino moved to New Zealand when he was four.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In 2004, at age 21, he played his first match for New Zealand against the Barbarians where he scored his first try, contributing to New Zealand's 47–19 victory that resulted in him becoming a man of the match.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] He also played a crucial role in the Rugby World Cup 2011 playing every match in the tournament.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] He scored four tries in the event which led to New Zealand winning the final against France 8–7.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Kaino was also a key member of the 2015 Rugby World Cup squad, where he played every match including a try he scored in the quarterfinals against France which New Zealand won 62–13.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] He scored again in the semifinals against South Africa, which New Zealand won 20–18.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] He played in the World Cup final against Australia where New Zealand won again 34–17 to become world champions for a record three times (1987, 2011, and 2015).
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Kaino is one of twenty New Zealand rugby players to have won the Rugby World Cup twice, back to back in 2011 and 2015.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In August 2015, the American Samoa Rugby Union Board selected Leota Toma Patu from the village of Leone as the coach for the Talavalu 15 men's team that represented American Samoa at the Ocean Cup 2015 in Papua New Guinea.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] A team from the Bureau of Outdoor Recreation conducted a parks survey on American Samoa in the 1960s.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Their team recommended sites at Cape Taputapu, Leʻala at Vailoatai, Aʻoloau (the plateau), Matautuloa Point, Nuʻuuli, Matafao Peak, Pago Pago, Vaiʻava Strait, Anasosopo, ʻAoa, Cape Matautuloa, and Aunuʻu Island.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] After an initial objection, Secretary Leʻiato gave his support and was appointed Chairman of the Territorial Parks and Recreation Committee.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The first field meeting for a parkland acquisition was held between Judge Morrow on behalf of the government and the village council of Vatia to make the Pola Island area a public park.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The dredge *Palolo* was hired from Upolu in January 1966 in order to dredge sand for Utulei Beach.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] A specialist in beach developments, Ala Varone of the Army, directed the project.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The centerpiece of the park was to be at the head of Pago Pago Harbor, where it proposed a 13-acre site created by the dredge.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The park would have facilities for sports and recreation as well as facilities for boats and the growing number of Asian immigrants arriving from Korea, Japan, and China.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The Department of Parks and Recreation was created by law in 1980 and the Parks Commission was also established.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In 1981, Governor Peter Tali Coleman appointed Fuga Tolani Teleso as Director of Parks and Recreation.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] On May 25, 1984, a groundbreaking ceremony was held at the Onesosopo reclamation to initiate work on the first park in the Eastern District.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] At the urging of Paul Cox, High Chief Nafanua of Falealupo, and the Bat Preservers Association, Congressman Fofō Iosefa Fiti Sunia introduced a bill in 1984 which would enter American Samoa into the Federal Fish and Wildlife Restoration Act.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The purpose of the bill was to protect the ancient paleotropical rainforests and the flying fox megabat.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The signing marked the beginning of American Samoa's entry into the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In July 1987, the National Park Service began establishing a federal park, the National Park of American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] An initial appropriation of $400,000 was made in 1989.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] It contains one of the world's most remarkable rainforest and coastal reef ecologies and spreads across three islands.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] One of the most popular sites on Tutuila Island include Pola Rock, a rise of sheer rock formations that protrudes over 400 feet (120 m) above the ocean's surface.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] On September 19, 1991, Governor Peter Tali Coleman and Department of the Interior secretary Manuel Lujan signed leases formalizing the establishment of the fiftieth U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa has seven areas designated as National Natural Landmarks on Tutuila Island.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] This program is administrated by the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] National Park Service and the areas contain unique ecological or geological features.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Except Vaiʻava Strait, none of the areas are within the National Park of American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Notable terrestrial species include the Pacific tree boa and the Samoa flying fox, which has a three-foot wingspread.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Two snake species can be found in American Samoa: The brahminy blind snake is found on Tutuila, while the Pacific tree boa occurs on Taʻū.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The islands are home to five species of geckos: Pacific slender-toed gecko, oceanic gecko, mourning gecko, stump-toed gecko, and house gecko.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Turtles include the threatened green sea turtle and the endangered hawksbill sea turtle.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Hawksbill sea turtles tend to nest on Tutuila beaches, while the green sea turtle is most common on Rose Atoll.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Tutuila has the highest number of nesting turtles, consisting of around fifty nesting females per year.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa is home to one species of amphibian: the cane toad.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Biologists estimate that there are over two million toads on Tutuila.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] 915 nearshore fish species have been recorded in American Samoa, compared to only 460 nearshore fish species in Hawaii.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] With over 950 species of native fish and 250 coral species, American Samoa has the greatest marine biodiversity in the United States.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The National Marine Sanctuary of American Samoa is the largest marine sanctuary in the U.S.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] It is home to over 150 species of coral, including some of the largest and oldest corals of their genus in the world.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Megabats are the only native mammal in American Samoa.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The islands are home to two species of fruit bats: Pacific flying fox and Samoa flying fox.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The sheath-tailed bat is another species found here, which is a smaller insect-eating bat.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] In 1992, the American Samoa Government banned the hunting of fruit bats to help their populations recover.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The Samoa flying fox is only found in Fiji and the Samoan Islands.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] From 1995 to 2000, the population of Samoa flying fox remained stable at about 900 animals on Tutuila, and 100 in the Manuʻa Islands.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] As of 2000, scientists from the American Samoa Department of Marine and Wildlife Resource estimated that there are fewer than 5,500 Pacific flying foxes in American Samoa, and an estimated 900 or fewer Samoa flying foxes.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The best and biggest known roost on Tutuila Island for the sheath-tailed bat is in the Anapeʻape Cove near Āfono.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Amalau Valley on Tutuila's north coast offers great roadside views of many bird species and both species of fruit bat.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The valley has been called a prime bird- and bat-watching area.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Sixteen of the Samoan Islands' 34 bird species are found nowhere else on Earth.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] This includes the critically endangered tooth-billed pigeon.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Four species of birds are only found in the Manuʻa Islands and not on Tutuila.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] These include American Samoa's only parrot, the blue-crowned lory.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Other special birds to Manuʻa are the lesser shrikebill and the friendly ground-dove.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The spotless crake has only been observed on Taʻū Island.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] There are more species of birds than all species of reptiles, mammals and amphibians combined.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Native land birds include two honeyeaters: cardinal honeyeater and wattled honeyeater.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Cardinal honeyeaters only occur on Tutuila Island.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The only endemic land bird to American Samoa is the Samoan starling.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Four pigeons are native to American Samoa: Pacific imperial pigeon, many-colored fruit dove, white-capped fruit dove, and shy ground dove.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The local government banned all pigeon hunting in 1992.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The many-colored fruit dove is one of the rarest birds that nest on Tutuila.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Studies in the 1980s estimated their population size at Tutuila to be only around 80 birds.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Amalau Valley has been described as the best place in American Samoa to observe the many-colored fruit dove.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The offshore islet of Pola Island near Vatia is a nesting site for many seabird species and an excellent area to observe seabirds.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The Pola region of Vatia and Rose Atoll are the only places in American Samoa where there are breeding colonies of red-footed boobies.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] Birds that depend on freshwater habitat include the Pacific reef heron and Pacific black duck, the Samoan Islands' only species of duck.
[src:fautasi/american-samoa-p02] The largest wetland areas are the pala lagoons in Nuʻuuli and Leone as well as Pala Lake on Aunuʻu Island.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The **New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa** is a maritime museum in Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] It is located on Hobson Wharf, adjacent to the Viaduct Harbour in central Auckland.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] It houses exhibitions spanning New Zealand's maritime history, from the first Polynesian explorers and settlers to modern day triumphs at the America's Cup.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The museum focuses on maritime stories of both the Auckland Region and New Zealand, with displays covering topics including immigration, trade, design, innovation, leisure, maritime history, Polynesian voyagers, and the history of the America's Cup.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] In addition to displays and art exhibitions, the New Zealand Maritime Museum collections include historic and cultural artifacts, replicas and working heritage vessels.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The New Zealand Maritime Museum is located on Hobson Wharf on the Auckland waterfront, adjacent to the Viaduct Basin and Princes Wharf.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The entrance of the museum incorporates the Launchman's Building, a structure built in 1920 which formerly housed a number of small boating companies.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The old Launchman's Building (Launch Offices) gained a Category II listing from Heritage New Zealand in 1981.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The main section of the maritime museum in an industrial-inspired structure located on Hobson Wharf.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] Heritage vessels owned by the museum are moored at the museum marina, and launched for sailings around the Waitematā Harbour.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] In 2010, the building won the Auckland Architecture Awards by the New Zealand Institute of Architects.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] Located outside of the Maritime Museum's entrance is *KZ1*, a yacht built to compete in the 1988 America's Cup, gifted to the museum by Fay Richwhite in 1990.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] Currently known as New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa, the museum opened in 1993 as Hobson Wharf: Auckland Maritime Museum.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] In 1996, the museum was renamed the New Zealand National Maritime Museum, a name given by Prime Minister Jim Bolger.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The museum rebranded as Voyager New Zealand Maritime Museum in November 2009, in order to reflect the museum's focus on exploration and discovery.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The organisation's current name, New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa, was adopted in 2014.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The organisation's Māori language name, Hui te Ananui a Tangaroa, was gifted by Hugh Kāwharu of Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei, and means "the Dwelling of Tangaroa", the atua of the oceans.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The establishment of a maritime history museum in Auckland began as a proposal by members of the Auckland Maritime Society, including Bill Laxon, Bob Hawkins, Cliff Hawkins and John Street, and by former members of the Auckland Harbour Board and Union Steam Ship Company.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The society had been established in 1958 as a section of the Auckland Institute and Museum, focused on promoting the study of ships.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] In 1973, the society explored the possibility of establishing a maritime museum on the shores of Lake Pupuke, which was found to be unsuitable.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] In November 1981, the Auckland Maritime Museum was established as a charitable trust.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The Auckland Ferry Terminal, where the museum had been storing archival materials, was explored as a potential site for the museum, but due to the cost of renovations this was decided against.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] In 1984, the museum appointed a director, Gordon Stevenson, former director of the Queen Elizabeth II Army Memorial Museum, and had begun exploring the possibility of using sheds on Princes Wharf.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] Plans for a smaller Princes Wharf museum were halted when the Auckland Harbour Board decided to redevelop Hobson Wharf, with the museum becoming a major part of the redevelopment.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] In 1989, Rodney Wilson was appointed as the new director for the museum, who led fundraising efforts to establish the institution.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] Plans for the museum at Hobson Wharf were announced in February 1989, with construction on the museum beginning in mid-1992.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The museum opened in August 1993, at an estimated cost of NZ$11.1 million.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] Many of the early maritime collections were long-term loans from Auckland War Memorial Museum, or donated items by members of the Auckland Maritime Society.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] While originally focusing on Auckland, the museum later expanded to become a national maritime museum.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] By 1996, financial difficulties led to staff redundancies at the museum, with museum director Richard Cassels resigning during the financial difficulties in 1998.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] In 2001, the New Zealand Government funded the Pacific Discovery Experience, a virtual reality exhibition depicting both the discovery of New Zealand by Polynesian peoples, and the later discovery by Europeans.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] A NZ$8 million extension to the northern end of the museum was built in 2009 to house a permanent exhibition, *Blue Water, Black Magic*, about Sir Peter Blake.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] It includes the original *NZL 32* (*Black Magic*).
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] *Blue Water, Black Magic* was developed in collaboration with Te Papa and Blake's daughter Sarah-Jane Blake.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] In 2010, an extension was added to the museum, housing an exhibition to New Zealand yachting which includes *NZL 32*, the yacht which won the 1995 America's Cup, suspended in the centre of the space.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] By 2018, the museum received approximately 160,000 annual visitors.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The museum was run by New Zealand National Maritime Museum Trust Board until March 2018, when it became a part of Regional Facilities Auckland, an Auckland Council-controlled organisation.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The organisation is now run by Tātaki Auckland Unlimited, the economic development agency of Auckland.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] In 2008, the Auckland Regional Amenities Funding Act was established, which ensured that funding for the New Zealand Maritime Museum was spread across all local councils in the Auckland Region.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] As of 2021, funding for the organisation primarily comes from the Auckland Council.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The first director of the Auckland Maritime Museum Trust was Gordon Stevenson, who was employed in January 1985.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] Rodney Wilson became the museum director in 1989, who was the director of the museum when it opened in 1993.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] In 1994, Wilson left to become the director of the Auckland War Memorial Museum.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] Wilson was replaced by Richard Cassels in the same year, who left in 1998.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] Cassels was followed by chief executive Larry Robbins in 1999, Craig Hobbs in 2007, and Paul Evans in 2008.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] By 2013, Murray Reade had become the chief executive officer.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] In 2013, former director of Toitū Otago Settlers Museum, Linda Wigley, became the director of the maritime museum, overseeing the redevelopment of the museum until her resignation in June 2014.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The current director of the maritime museum, Vincent Lipanovich, has held the position since 2015.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] In 2018, the institution had 166 volunteers, working as tour guides, maintenance and operational crew for heritage vessels, model makers and learning programme assistants.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] Since 2003, personnel from the Royal New Zealand Navy have been occasionally seconded to the museum to assist with maintenance of the ships and exhibition objects.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] In addition, the museum holds collection items focusing on subjects including whaling, modern commercial shipping, lifeboat, pilotage and coastguard services, marine surveying, maritime arts and crafts and maritime recreation.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The museum also operates *Aotearoa One*, launched 2013, described on the museum's website as "a modern take on a traditional waka", which no longer has scheduled sailings.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The museum previously operated the *Rapaki steam crane*, a 1926 floating steam crane, built at Paisley in Scotland for the Lyttelton Harbour Board, which was permanently removed and dismantled in December 2018.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The vessel had been used in active service for three years during World War II, being used to support the United States Navy at New Caledonia.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] The museum has a collection of over 130 watercraft, including the 1933 John L.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] Hacker-designed mahogany and kauri speedboat *Jon-El*, *The Frances*, an early 20th century vessel owned by the Shakespear family, and Paul Caffyn's kayak *Isadora*.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] Other vessels include the *Tainui*, an 1860 whaling vessel, P-class sailing dinghies designed by Harry Highet, *Mammoth*, a moth-class dinghy, and the Karlich hull used by Olympic Gold medalist rowers, the 1972 New Zealand eight.
[src:fautasi/aotearoa-one] *Tatarai*, a Baurua voyager canoe from Kiribati built in 1976 by Kiribati islanders and photographer Jim Siers using traditional methods, and sailed from Kiribati to Fiji in 1976, is also held in the museum's collections.
[src:fautasi/apilan] Apilan is a native Malay word, not descended from any foreign word.
[src:fautasi/apilan] It is also a standalone word, because the syllable is api-lan instead of apil-an.
[src:fautasi/apilan] The term comes from Malay word *kota* which in turn comes from the Sanskrit word कोट्ट (kota) which means fort, fortress, castle, fortified house, fortification, works, city, town, or place encircled by walls.
[src:fautasi/apilan] The word *mara* may come from Malay word meaning "appear before", "forward", "come", "moved to the front", "forward", and "advanced".
[src:fautasi/apilan] Thus it can be interpreted as "breastwork before a cannon" or "breastwork at the front".
[src:fautasi/apilan] According to the Great Indonesian Dictionary (KBBI), kota mara means (1) Wall on a ship to protect men mounting the cannon (2) Terrace or wall over a castle which a cannon is mounted.
[src:fautasi/apilan] Warington Smyth, kota mara means transverse deck bulkhead at stem and stern (of a ship).
[src:fautasi/apilan] *Benteng* itself means fort, battery, or redoubt.
[src:fautasi/apilan] Singapore resident John Crawfurd recorded Malay piracy near Singapore waters.
[src:fautasi/apilan] The Malay pirate ships of the time were 40–50 feet (12–15 m) long with 15-foot (4.6 m) beam.
[src:fautasi/apilan] The decks were made of split *nibong* wood.
[src:fautasi/apilan] Smaller pirate craft put up thick plank bulwarks [apilan] when fighting, while larger ones like those of the Lanun people had bamboo ledges hanging over their gunwales, with a protecting breastwork [kota mara] of plaited rattan about 3 feet (0.91 meters) high.
[src:fautasi/apilan] A crew might consist of 20–30 men, augmented with oarsmen of captured slaves.
[src:fautasi/apilan] Small craft would have nine oars per side; larger ones would be double-banked, with an upper tier of oarsmen seated on the bulwark projection hidden behind rattan breastwork.
[src:fautasi/apilan] Pirate armament included a stockade near the bow, with iron or brass 4-pounders, and another stockade aft, generally with two swivel guns.
[src:fautasi/apilan] They also might have four or five brass swivels, or rantaka, on each side.
[src:fautasi/apilan] They have bamboo shields, and were armed with spears, keris, muskets and other firearms they could get.
[src:fautasi/armadahan] The single outrigger float (*palangoy*) on the starboard side was either two bamboo poles lashed together or a flattened elongated beam.
[src:fautasi/armadahan] It was connected to the hull by a length of bamboo around 6 m (20 ft) long, known as the *batangan*.
[src:fautasi/armadahan] It also featured a counter-balance beam projecting off the port side known as the *paltek*.
[src:fautasi/armadahan] The *batangan* is connected to the hull by a wooden outrigger beam collar, with braces on the forward, cross, and aft.
[src:fautasi/armadahan] At the stern is a small socket for the rudder tiller.
[src:fautasi/armadahan] Three or four other small holes are also drilled along the midcenter of the dugout to let the water enter the craft, allowing live fish to be stored in the hull when fishing.
[src:fautasi/armadahan] These holes are also used to drain the craft when beached.
[src:fautasi/armadahan] Each boat also has a cooking area on the aft, usually a wood or kerosene portable stove.
[src:fautasi/armadahan] In modern times, these types of boats are usually motorized or paddled.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] They range from small dugout canoes to large lashed-lug plank-built vessels.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] Their hull configurations include monohulls as well as catamarans and outrigger boats (single-outrigger boats and trimarans).
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] Traditional sail types include a variety of distinctively Austronesian crab-claw and tanja configurations, though modern vessels are typically motorized.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] These vessels allowed the migrations of the Austronesian peoples during the Austronesian expansion (starting at around 3000 to 1500 BC from Taiwan and Island Southeast Asia) throughout the islands of the Indo-Pacific, reaching as far as Madagascar, New Zealand, and Easter Island.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] They were also used to establish trading routes, including the Austronesian maritime trade network which formed the maritime leg of the spice trade and later, the maritime silk road.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] Austronesians used distinctive sailing technologies, namely the catamaran, the outrigger ship, tanja sail and the crab claw sail.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] This allowed them to colonize a large part of the Indo-Pacific region during the Austronesian expansion starting at around 3000 to 1500 BC, and ending with the colonization of Easter Island and New Zealand in the 10th to 13th centuries AD.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] Prior to the 16th century Colonial Era, Austronesians were the most widespread ethnolinguistic group, spanning half the planet from Easter Island in the eastern Pacific Ocean to Madagascar in the western Indian Ocean.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] They also established vast maritime trading networks, among which is the Neolithic precursor to what would become the Maritime Silk Road.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] The simplest form of all ancestral Austronesian boats had five parts.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] The bottom part consists of a single piece of hollowed-out log.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] At the sides were two planks, and two horseshoe-shaped wood pieces formed the prow and stern.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] These were fitted tightly together edge-to-edge by sewing or with dowels inserted into holes in between, and then lashed to each other with ropes (made from rattan or fibre) wrapped around protruding lugs on the planks.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] This characteristic and ancient Austronesian boatbuilding practice is known as the "lashed-lug" technique.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] They were commonly caulked with pastes made from various plants as well as tapa bark and fibres which would expand when wet, further tightening joints and making the hull watertight.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] They formed the shell of the boat, which was then reinforced by horizontal ribs.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] Shipwrecks of Austronesian ships can be identified from this construction, as well as the absence of metal nails.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] Austronesian ships traditionally had no central rudders but were instead steered using an oar on one side.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] They also independently developed various sail types during the Neolithic, beginning with the crab claw sail (more usually called the "oceanic lateen" or the "oceanic sprit") at around 1500 BCE.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] They are used throughout the range of the Austronesian Expansion, from Maritime Southeast Asia, to Micronesia, Island Melanesia, Polynesia, and Madagascar.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] Crab claw sails are rigged fore-and-aft and can be tilted and rotated relative to the wind.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] They evolved from V-shaped perpendicular square sails in which the two spars converge at the base of the hull.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] The simplest form of the crab claw sail (also with the widest distribution) is composed of a triangular sail supported by two light spars (sometimes erroneously called "sprits") on each side.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] They were originally mastless, and the entire assembly was taken down when the sails were lowered.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] Austronesian rigs were used for double-canoe (catamaran), single-outrigger (on the windward side), or double-outrigger boat configurations, in addition to monohulls.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] There are several distinct types of crab claw rigs, but unlike western rigs, they do not have fixed conventional names.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] The need to propel larger and more heavily laden boats led to the increase in vertical sail.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] However this introduced more instability to the vessels.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] In addition to the unique invention of outriggers to solve this, the sails were also leaned backwards and the converging point moved further forward on the hull.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] This new configuration required a loose "prop" in the middle of the hull to hold the spars up, as well as rope supports on the windward side.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] This allowed more sail area (and thus more power) while keeping the center of effort low and thus making the boats more stable.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] The prop was later converted into fixed or removable canted masts where the spars of the sails were actually suspended by a halyard from the masthead.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] This type of sail is most refined in Micronesian proas which could reach very high speeds.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] These configurations are sometimes known as the "crane sprit" or the "crane spritsail".
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] Micronesian, Island Melanesian, and Polynesian single-outrigger vessels also used the canted mast configuration to uniquely develop shunting.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] In shunting vessels, both ends are alike, and the boat is sailed in either direction, but it has a fixed leeward side and a windward side.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] The boat is shunted from beam reach to beam reach to change direction, with the wind over the side, a low-force procedure.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] The bottom corner of the crab claw sail is moved to the other end, which becomes the bow as the boat sets off back the way it came.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] The mast usually hinges, adjusting the rake or angle of the mast.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] The crab claw configuration used on these vessels is a low-stress rig, which can be built with simple tools and low-tech materials, but it is extremely fast.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] On a beam reach, it may be the fastest simple rig.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] Another evolution of the basic crab claw sail is the conversion of the upper spar into a fixed mast.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] In Polynesia, this gave the sail more height while also making it narrower, giving it a shape reminiscent of crab pincers (hence "crab claw" sail).
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] This was also usually accompanied by the lower spar becoming more curved.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] The conversion of the prop to a fixed mast in the crab claw sail led to the much later invention of the tanja sail (also known variously and misleadingly as the canted square sail, canted rectangular sail, boomed lugsail, or balance lugsail).
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] Tanja sails were rigged similarly to crab claw sails and also had spars on both the head and the foot of the sails; but they were square or rectangular with the spars not converging into a point.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] They are generally mounted on one or two (rarely three or more) bipod or tripod masts, usually made from thick bamboo.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] The masts have curved heads with grooves for attaching the halyards.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] The lower part of two of the bamboo poles of the mast assembly have holes that are fitted unto the ends of a cross-wise length of timber on the deck, functioning like a hinge.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] The forward part of the mast assembly had a forelock.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] By unlocking it, the mast can be lowered across the ship.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] Despite the similarity of its appearance to western square rigs, the tanja is a fore-and-aft rig similar to a lugsail.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] The sail was suspended from the upper spar ("yard"), while the lower spar functioned like a boom.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] When set fore-and-aft, the spars extend forward of the mast by about a third of their lengths.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] When running before the wind, they are set perpendicular to the hull, similar to a square rig.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] The sail can be rotated around the mast (lessening the need for steering with the rudders) and tilted to move the center of pull forward or aft.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] The sail can even be tilted completely horizontally, becoming wing-like, to lift the bow above incoming waves.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] The sail is reefed by rolling it around the lower spar.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] In addition to the tanja sails, ships with the tanja rigs also have bowsprits set with a quadrilateral headsail, sometimes also canted as depicted in the Borobudur ships.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] In the colonial era, these were replaced by triangular western-style jibs (often several in later periods), and the tanja sails themselves were slowly replaced with western rigs like gaff rigs.
[src:fautasi/austronesian-vessels] The following is an incomplete list of traditional Austronesian vessels.
[src:fautasi/fautasi] A **fautasi** (/ˌfɑːʊˈtɑːsi/ *FAH-uu-TAH-see*) is a Samoan boat, similar to a longboat.
[src:fautasi/fautasi] Fautasi boats are around 100 feet (30 m) in length and can accommodate a rowing crew of 50.
[src:fautasi/fautasi] A coxwain uses a drum to beat a tempo to coordinate the rowing.
[src:fautasi/fautasi] The meaning of *fautasi* is "to build as one," which reflects the structure of the boat build from one hollowed out tree, in contrast to a paopao.
[src:fautasi/fautasi] Prior to the use of modern-day ferries, fautasi were the main mode of transport between islands such as Upolu and Savai'i.
[src:fautasi/fautasi] Today, fautasi are mainly used in racing events.
[src:fautasi/fautasi] Traditionally, men involved in the racing spent eight weeks away from their families and other luxuries, and training with their captain.
[src:fautasi/fautasi] The races take place during the Independent State of Samoa's Independence Days week celebrations in June.
[src:fautasi/fautasi] In American Samoa, the race take place during Flag Day marking the acceptance by the Samoans of the Deed of Cession.
[src:fautasi/fautasi] The sport is mainly a men-only sport (faaga tama), but in 2013, an all-women crew participated in the fautasi race.
[src:fautasi/fautasi] The first woman to become a fautasi Captain was Zita Martel in 2001.
[src:fautasi/fautasi] Entrants from Independent State of Samoa, American Samoa, Tonga and Hawaii have participated.
[src:fautasi/fautasi] Fautasi are traditionally made of hollowed-out trees.
[src:fautasi/fautasi] More modern fautasi are made out of fiberglass which is more versatile.
